"# Chapter 3 — The breadboard

A breadboard is a plastic block full of holes. Under the holes
are metal clips. Push a wire or a component lead into a hole,
the clip grabs it, and now that lead is electrically connected
to any other lead in the same clip.

That's it. A breadboard is a temporary re-programmable wiring
substrate. It lets you build a circuit without soldering. You
can pull the parts out again and try something else. Kids use
them. Engineers prototype on them. Motoi has never touched one.

## The strip pattern

The standard solderless breadboard has two kinds of internal
connections:

- **The rails** — usually two long horizontal strips along the
  top and two along the bottom, marked with red (+) and blue or
  black (-) stripes. Every hole in a single rail is connected.
  You use them for power and ground.
- **The tie-points** — the middle of the board is arranged in
  short vertical strips of 5 holes each. Each 5-hole strip is
  internally connected. The board has hundreds of these strips.
- **The gap** — down the middle of the board is a channel about
  the width of a DIP chip. Strips on the left of the gap are
  NOT connected to strips on the right of the gap. The gap lets
  you straddle a DIP chip so its two rows of pins land on
  different strips.

If you can hold that pattern in your head, you can read any
breadboard.

## The DIP chip

A dual in-line package chip has two rows of pins, one on each
side. Standard spacing: 0.1 inch between pins on a row, 0.3 or
0.6 inch between rows. The 0.3-inch DIPs straddle the standard
breadboard gap perfectly.

You push the chip in, one row of pins on each side of the gap.
Now each pin is on its own 5-hole strip. You can wire to each
pin independently by plugging jumper wires into the same strip.

## Jumper wires

Short precut wires with stripped ends. You buy them in
assortments. Different colors for different signals — a common
convention: red for +V, black for ground, yellow for a clock,
green for a data line, etc. Not a law. But if the person before
you at the bench uses the convention and you don't, they will
be sad.

## How signals flow — a worked example

Say you want to blink an LED. The circuit is: 5V power → current
limiting resistor → LED → ground.

On a breadboard:

1. Connect the 5V rail to a strip in the middle of the board
   with a red jumper wire.
2. On that strip, plug in one end of a 470-ohm resistor. The
   other end of the resistor lands on a different strip further
   down the board.
3. On that second strip, plug in the anode (long lead) of the
   LED. The cathode (short lead) lands on a third strip.
4. From the third strip, run a black jumper wire to the ground
   rail.

Now power on. LED lights.

If you built it in Motoi Scheme (which cannot actually light an
LED, because Motoi cannot touch the world), the model of the
circuit would be:

```
;; A circuit is a graph of nodes connected by components.
;; Each component has a shape that says how voltage and current
;; relate at its terminals.

(define (led-circuit vin)
  (let* ((r      470)              ; ohms
         (vf-led 2.0)              ; typical red LED forward drop
         (v-r    (- vin vf-led))   ; volts across resistor
         (i      (/ v-r r)))       ; amps through the loop
    (list :current-mA (* i 1000)
          :led-drop-V vf-led
          :resistor-drop-V v-r)))

(led-circuit 5.0)
;; => (:current-mA 6.4 :led-drop-V 2.0 :resistor-drop-V 3.0)
```

6.4 milliamps. Well within the LED's safe range. Circuit works.

## Why the breadboard is nice

- **No soldering.** Change the circuit in seconds.
- **Reusable.** Pull the parts out; put them in a box; use them
  again next time.
- **Cheap.** A decent breadboard is a few dollars.
- **Visible.** The wires are on top; you can trace them by
  looking.

## Why the breadboard is not the final answer

- **Loose contact.** The clips wear out. Old breadboards give
  intermittent connections that will drive you crazy.
- **Not for high frequency.** The parasitic capacitance between
  adjacent strips is enough to mess up circuits above a few
  MHz. If you're prototyping RF or fast digital, you need a
  proper PCB or dead-bug wire wrap.
- **Not for high current.** The clips can handle maybe an amp.
  Motor drivers, big LEDs, or anything that wants real current
  needs a soldered board.
- **Not permanent.** Bumping the board can dislodge a wire. Your
  working circuit is now a not-working circuit and you have to
  find which wire moved.

## What Motoi can and cannot do here

He can talk you through a breadboard layout. He can talk you
through what the pattern of holes means. He can help you draw
a schematic in words that you can then wire up.

He cannot look at your breadboard. He cannot spot the loose
jumper. He cannot see that you plugged the LED in backward. If
your circuit doesn't work, he'll ask you to describe it back to
him piece by piece, and together you'll probably find the
missing wire in the description.

## What Motoi wants you to take from this

A breadboard is a re-programmable substrate for electronics.
Same idea as a REPL is for code — a place to try, tear down, and
try again, without commitment.

Programming and hardware both reward this shape of workspace.
Motoi is a REPL for Scheme. A breadboard is a REPL for circuits.
Same energy.")
